1. Write a function that models enzyme kinetics using the quasi-steady state assumption of Michaelis-Menten kinetics. (it will be applied in 2)¶

In [2]:
def MM_QSSA(y, t, Km, kcat):
    E  = y[0]
    S  = y[1]
    x = y[2]    # ES = x
    P  = y[3]

    # Quasi-Steady State Assumption
    x = (E0 * S) / (Km + S)

    dEdt  = 0
    dSdt  = -kcat * x
    dxdt = 0
    dPdt  = kcat * x

    return [dEdt, dSdt, dxdt, dPdt]

2. Plot the changes in product concentration using Michaelis-Menten Kinetics with the quasi-steady state approximation using the following parameters:¶

KM = (k-1 + k2) / k1

$K_{cat}$ = 10 $s^{-1}$

$K_{M}$ = 110 $μ_{M}$

Initial Enzyme Concentration = 50 $μ_{M}$

Initial Substrate Concentration = 500 $μ_{M}$

In [3]:
# Set parameters
kcat = 10.0  # Rate constant for the breakdown of ES into products
Km = 110.0   # MM constant

# Initial conditions
E0 = 50.0    # Initial enzyme concentration
S0 = 500.0   # Initial substrate concentration
ES0 = 0.0   # Initial ES complex concentration
P0 = 0.0   # Initial product concentration
initial_conditions = [E0, S0, ES0, P0]

# Time points for simulation
t = np.linspace(0, 5, 100)

# Simulation using Monod QSSA function
solution = odeint(MM_QSSA, initial_conditions, t, args = (Km, kcat))

# Extract concentrations over time
E, S, x, P = solution.T

# Plot results
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 8), dpi = 369)
sns.lineplot(P, label = 'Product Concentration').set(title = 'Product Concentration with Michaelis-Menten Kinetics for QSSA')
plt.xlabel('Time (s)')
plt.ylabel('Concentration (μM)')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

a. Explain with words and illustrate with a graph and the values bellow what happens when you change $K_{M}$:

# Set parameters
kcat = 10.0  
KM_values = [1, 20, 100, 200, 500]  # Different MM constants

# Initial conditions
E0 = 50.0    # Initial enzyme concentration
S0 = 500.0   # Initial substrate concentration
ES0 = 0.0   # Initial ES complex concentration
P0 = 0.0   # Initial product concentration
initial_conditions = [E0, S0, ES0, P0]

# Time points for simulation
t = np.linspace(0, 8, 100)

# Plot results for different KM values
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 8), dpi = 369)
for KM in KM_values:
    solution = odeint(MM_QSSA, initial_conditions, t, args = (KM, kcat))
    P = solution[:, 3]  # Extract product concentration
    sns.lineplot(P, label = f'KM = {KM} μM').set(title = 'Effect of KM on Product Concentration')

plt.xlabel('Time (s)')
plt.ylabel('Product Concentration (μM)')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
